ABUJA – Chief Whip of the Senate, Orji Uzor Kalu, has urged the Federal Government to create special funds to support entrepreneurs in the country, as part of moves to cushion the biting economic situation. Kalu spoke in Abuja when he opened Tastia Restaurant and Bakery with a capacity for more than 200 diners. Tastia Restaurant and Bakery of Nigeria’s leading Quick Service Restaurants (QSR). The new outlet is the seventh and it’s located at Adetokunbo Ademola Crescent, Abuja. Kalu commended Mr. Agwu, the owner of the outlet for the initiative of a classy restaurant and urged him to ensure that the standard he started was maintained. He noted that the bane of the hospitality business is poor maintenance culture. The lawmaker further commended him for creating jobs for Nigerians, noting that he should continue to expand so that more jobs will be created. Kalu said the government should create policies that will encourage more Nigerians to go into entrepreneurship to boost the hospitality business in Nigeria The restaurant’s owner, Mr. Kesta Agwu, told reporters during a briefing that more than N500 million had been spent on the new establishment, which has a seating capacity of 220–230 people and is currently the biggest restaurant in Abuja. POLL Meanwhile, Thelma Elijah, the General Manager of the new outlet, will be operating à la carte menu as opposed to the usual QRS offered at other Tastia outlets. She said: “There’s the VIP section, a space for birthdays and other events, another section where people can come and rest, buffet services, home delivery and more. “Free meals were provided for the first 50 people at the launch as a way to give back to loyal customers who have been with us since we opened our first restaurant in June 2020.”